@node About "About CompilAIBB..."
    @{fg highlight}About CompilAIBB :@{fg text} What is that compilation.

@{u}CompilAIBB@{uu} is a collection of files,  @{"modules" link Modules}, created with the @{"AIBB" link AIBB} soft-
ware,  and enclosing informations about  the @{"hardware" link HardConfig} and @{"software" link SoftConfig}  setup,
and the performances of a given @{"Amiga" link Amiga} setup.

This is the  1.1 version of @{u}CompilAIBB@{uu},  constituted of modules  made with
6.0 or newer versions of AIBB.

The idea of  CompilAIBB came from  discussions about performances  held on
the french mailing-list created by @{"Cédric Beust" link CedricBeust}  :  amiga@sophia.inria.fr.
This list is coupled to the newsgroup : fr.comp.sys.amiga.

@{u}CompilAIBB@{uu} is free,  but I would  greatly appreciate  a nice postcard from
where you live if you use it.


This release of @{u}CompilAIBB@{uu} is dedicated to @{"Pierre Carrette" link PierreCarrette}.
@endnode

@node Modules "AIBB modules"
    @{fg highlight}AIBB Modules :@{fg text} What are they, how to use them.

An @{"AIBB" link AIBB} module is a file,  small enough (1760 bytes),  in which are summed
up the @{"hardware" link HardConfig}  and @{"software" link SoftConfig} setup  together with the results  of all the
tests that AIBB know to apply to a given @{"Amiga" link Amiga} setup.

        @{"    Consult    " link Consult}  How to read a module
        @{"     Create    " link Create }  How to make a module
@endnode

@node HardConfig "Hardware setup"
    @{fg highlight}Hardware setup :@{fg text} Examples.

 - processor kind : 68000, 68020, 68030, @{"80486" link 80486}, etc
 - its frequency : 14 MHz, 33 MHz, etc
 - possible presence of mathematics coprocessor
 - specialized chipset identification : Agnus, Denise, Alice, etc
 - possible presence of expansion boards
 - etc
@endnode

@node SoftConfig "Software setup"
    @{fg highlight}Software setup :@{fg text} Examples.

 - Kickstart version, i.e. system version :
     37.175 for 2.04, 40.63 for le 3.1, etc
 - system main libraries versions :
     exec.library, graphics.library, etc
 - Kickstart locations : ROM or RAM
@endnode

@node Consult "Consult a module"
    @{fg highlight}Consult a module :@{fg text} How to read it.

There are two ways  to consult  a module  :  with @{"AIBB" link AIBB} itself  or with the
ModInfo program released with the 6.1 version of AIBB.

With AIBB, you must select one of the four comparison machines in the @{b}Main@{ub}
AIBB screen  (the four boxes under the "@{b}you@{ub}" box  for the current machine)
and thus  get the screen summing up  the features of  that machine.  Then,
just select the menu option :

      @{b}Options@{ub} / @{b}Load New@{ub} / @{b}Load From Module File@{ub}

It remains only  to select the module of your choice  with the help of the
file requester.  The features of the machine with wich the module was made
are then displayed.  Back to the Main screen, you can compare your machine
to the  other four,  or,  in "review"  mode  (menu option  @{b}Special@{ub} / @{b}Enter
Review Mode@{ub}), this four machines to each other.

The  ModInfo  utility allows  to translate  in text understandable  by any
mortal the content of a module.  Its use is one the most simple.  From any
shell, type :

      @{b}ModInfo nom_de_module@{ub}

The text then scrolls to the screen.  You will find convenient to redirect
the output to a file :

      @{b}ModInfo >RAM:microsofts_grosprofits.txt nom_de_module@{ub}
@endnode

@node Create "Create a module"
    @{fg highlight}Create a module :@{fg text} Instructions.

You just need, in the @{b}Main@{ub} screen, to choice the menu option :

      @{b}Special@{ub} / @{b}All Tests : Make Module@{ub}

You must pay attention  @{i}to configure  your machine right@{ui}  before to launch
this option  :  this operation is long enough (about one hour with a stock
A2000,  at least 15 minutes with a 25 MHz 68030) and can't be interrupted.
Your setup must be equivalent to the one of the machines which you want to
compare to :  @{i}caches@{ui} and @{i}burst modes@{ui} use, @{i}resolution@{ui} and @{i}number of colors@{ui},
interferences of progams modifying the system, etc.
@endnode

@node HowToGet "Obtainment"
    @{fg highlight}Obtainment :@{fg text} How to get @{u}CompilAIBB@{uu}.

A new @{u}CompilAIBB@{uu} version will be released each time enough new modules are
in my possession. The release can be done in three different ways :

  @{"          By FTP           " link FTP          } If you have total Internet access
  @{"         By e-mail         " link GetEMail     } If you have partial Internet access
  @{"   By normal, snail mail   " link SendSnailMail} If you don't have Internet access at all
@endnode

@node FTP "By FTP"
    @{fg highlight}By FTP :@{fg text} Some addresses.

Each new @{u}CompilAIBB@{uu} version will uploaded to the following FTP sites :

    @{fg fill}avahi.inria.fr@{fg text}  in @{b}/pub/Amiga@{ub}

    @{"Aminet" link Aminet}          in @{b}/pub/aminet/util/moni@{ub}

The name of the file to be downloaded is : @{b}CompilAIBBx.x.lha@{ub} (where "x.x"
is the version, here 1.0).
@endnode

@node GetEMail "By e-mail"
    @{fg highlight}By e-mail :@{fg text} You'll have to subscribe.

Send an empty message  of which the subject is  "@{b}CompilAIBB by e-mail@{ub}"  to
one of the two following addresses :

    @{fg fill}Yann-Erick.Proy@Imag.fr@{fg text}   or   @{fg fill}Proy@Merlin-Gerin.fr@{fg text}

@{u}CompilAIBB@{uu}  will be sent to you each time it is released in the form of an
uuencoded lha archive. In order not to overload mailboxes, this archive
will contain only the modules and the english AmigaGuide file.
@endnode

@node AIBB "AIBB"
    @{fg highlight}AIBB :@{fg text} What is that software.

@{"AIBB" link AIBBStupid}  (@{i}Amiga Intuition Based Benchmarks@{ui})  is a software for evaluation and
comparison of  performances of  @{"Amiga" link Amiga} setups.  AIBB allows  to get precise
informations about @{"hardware" link HardConfig} and @{"software" link SoftConfig} setup of the tested machine too.

Its author is @{i}Peter LaMonte Koop@{ui},  whose address is (according to the AIBB
6.5 documentation, dated 1993) :

    @{fg fill}lkoop@tigger.stcloud.msus.edu@{fg text}   or   @{fg fill}f00012@kanga.stcloud.msus.edu@{fg text}

Alas, Peter has not logged on to both sites since the beginning of october
1994.
@endnode

@node Evolution "Evolution"
    @{fg highlight}Evolution of CompilAIBB :@{fg text} It depends on you.

A new @{u}CompilAIBB@{uu} version will be released each time enough new modules are
in my possession.  If you own a setup different  from the ones in already,
don't waste time  :  create  a module and  send it  to me with  a detailed
description of your machine !

Be careful to activate all caches and burst modes,  copy-back, etc, of the
processor.  On the contrary,  unactivate every exotic patch that may alter
the performances  of your  machine  (or make  a second  module).  The only
exception to this rule is the Kickstart copy in RAM : widely practised, it
is preferred to Kickstart in ROM (you can always send me both modules).

  @{"        By e-mail          " link SendEMail    } If you have Internet access
  @{"   By normal, snail mail   " link SendSnailMail} If you don't have Internet access

Furthermore,  @{u}CompilAIBB@{uu} may contain uncomplete or absolutely wrong infor-
mations about some boards or setups. I would be grateful to you if you let
me know it, in order to improve the quality of this document.

I would appreciate suggestions about that poor english translation too...
@endnode

@node SendEMail "By e-mail"
    @{fg highlight}By e-mail :@{fg text} Uuencode and mail.

In order to do it,  you must uuencode the module you got,  because it is a
binary file.  Then, you only need to insert the coded file in a message to
be sent to one of these addresses :

    @{fg fill}Yann-Erick.Proy@Imag.fr@{fg text}   or   @{fg fill}Proy@Merlin-Gerin.fr@{fg text}
@endnode

@node SendSnailMail "By normal, snail mail"
    @{fg highlight}By normal, snail mail :@{fg text} You can kill two birds with one stone.

Send me your @{"module" link Modules} on a floppy disk to the following address, if you join
to it a  sufficiently  stamped  enveloppe,  I will  send back  to you your
floppy disk with the very last @{u}CompilAIBB@{uu} version :

            @{fg fill}Yann-Erick PROY
            CompilAIBB
            44, avenue GAMBETTA
            F-74000 ANNECY
            FRANCE@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Use "Usage"
    @{fg highlight}Usage :@{fg text} Goals for using @{u}CompilAIBB@{uu}.

This compilation of AIBB @{"modules" link Modules} can serve to other purposes than only to
satisfy your curiosity :

@{" Comparing accelerating boards       " link Accel} Which one to choose ?
@{" Comparing two Kickstart versions    " link Kick } Is the upgrade to be done ?
@{" Observing the effects of patches    " link Patch} How to improve performances ?
@endnode

@node Accel "Comparing accelerating boards"
    @{fg highlight}Comparing accelerating boards :@{fg text} Which one to choose ?
    
@{u}CompilAIBB@{uu} can help you  in your choice by giving you,  thanks to @{"AIBB" link AIBB}, an
indication about relative performances of the boards between which you are
hesitating.  Take care however not to rely too much upon the results given
by AIBB :

  - all @{"modules" link Modules}  from the compilation  haven't been done  in the  same
    conditions unfortunately ;
  - AIBB may be wrong as well ;
  - the execution speed of AIBB tests may not represent the one of the
    application(s) you use  (the amount of memory  and the fastness of
    disks accesses may greatly influence this one).

In any case, you should have read the whole AIBB doocumentation to pretend
understand its results without making too many errors.

Likewise, the greatest prudence is recommended towards the informations
given in this document about memory capacities, expansion abilities, etc,
of the various boards cited. @{u}CompilAIBB@{uu} don't pretend to be exhaustive as
well.

@endnode

@node Kick "Comparing two Kickstart versions"
    @{fg highlight}Comparing two Kickstart versions :@{fg text} Is the upgrade to be done ?

@{u}CompilAIBB@{uu} can inform you  about relative performances of  successive ver-
sions of the system software of the @{"Amiga" link Amiga},  that is to say,  for the grea-
test part, the Kickstart. Indeed, some of its @{"modules" link Modules} only differ by their
KickStart version. These are examples :

  Comparing KS 2.0 and 3.1 :
@{"A2000-07-ROM20            " link A2000-XX-ROM20    } A2000 B, KS 2.04 in ROM
@{"A2000-07-ROM31            " link A2000-07-ROM31    } A2000 B, KS 3.1 in ROM
@{"GFr40-33-ROM20-GVP        " link GFr40-33-ROM20-GVP} GForce 040 33 MHz, KS 2.04 in ROM
@{"GFr40-33-ROM31-GVP        " link GFr40-33-ROM31-GVP} GForce 040 33 MHz, KS 3.1 in ROM

  Comparing KS 3.0 et 3.1 :
@{"A3001-28-FAS30-GVP        " link A3001-28-FAS3X-GVP} GVP A3001 28 MHz, KS 3.0 in RAM
@{"A3001-28-FAS31-GVP        " link A3001-28-FAS3X-GVP} GVP A3001 28 MHz, KS 3.1 in RAM

The "WritePixel",  "EllipseTest" and  "TGTest" tests,  which call upon the
graphical  layers  of the system  software a lot,  allow to  apreciate the
improvement done in this domain by the 3.1 Kickstart.
@endnode

@node Patch "Observing the effects of patches"
    @{fg highlight}Observing the effects of patches :@{fg text} How to improve performances ?

@{u}CompilAIBB@{uu} can help you  to optimize your setup  by revealing to you,  for
instance,  which system @{"patches" link PatchSofts} may improve,  or, on the contrary, degrade
the performances of your machine.  The easiest to use and  the most common
is of course the Kickstart relocation in fast 32 bits memory :

@{"A-530-40-ROM20-GVP        " link A-530-40-XXX20} GVP A530 40 MHz, KS 2.04 in ROM
@{"A-530-40-FAS20-GVP        " link A-530-40-XXX20} GVP A530 40 MHz, KS 2.04 in RAM
@{"MTec3-28-ROM30-FPU16      " link MTec3-28-ROM30-FPU16} M-Tec 68030 28 MHz, 68882 16 MHz, KS 3.0 in ROM
@{"Viper-28-FAS30-FPU16      " link Viper-28-FAS30-FPU16} Viper 1230 28 MHz, 68882 16 MHz, KS 3.0 in RAM

@{"A4030-25-ROM30_FPU33      " link A4030-25-ROM30_FPU33} A4000/030,
@{"A4030-25-ROM30_FPU33_Patch" link A4030-25-ROM30_FPU33} A4000/030, CopyMemQuicker, Execpatch, etc

You can also observe the degrading of performances in memory accesses when
using a virtual memory software such as VMM 2.0 :

@{"A1230-50-FAS30-GVP        " link A1230-50-FAS30-GVP} GVP A1230 50 MHz
@{"A1230-50-FAS30-GVP_VMM    " link A1230-50-FAS30-GVP} GVP A1230 50 MHz, VMM

Furthermore,  @{u}CompilAIBB@{uu}  allow to  observe  the effects of  miscellaneous
settings with caches activated or not, etc :

@{"A1230-50-FAS30-GVP        " link A1230-50-FAS30-GVP} GVP A1230 50 MHz
@{"A1230-50-FAS30-GVP_NoDtCch" link A1230-50-FAS30-GVP} GVP A1230 50 MHz, datacache on
@endnode

@node PatchSofts "Patches"
    @{fg highlight}Patches :@{fg text} Some softwares

@{u}AddMem@{uu}, from @{i}Martin Schlodder@{ui}, free.

@{u}CPUClear@{uu}, from @{i}Peter Simons@{ui}, free.

@{u}FBL@{uu} (FasterBLit), from @{i}Arthur Hagen@{ui}, free.

@{u}ROMTagMem@{uu}, from @{i}John Matthews@{ui}, free.

@{u}Set040@{uu},  from @{i}Nic Wilson@{ui},  shareware  ($ 25).  But his electronic address
(@{fg fill}nicw@wilson.adsp.sub.org@{fg text})  is not  valid  anymore...  Who knows  his new
address or, at least knows if his postal address is still valid ?


All these softwares are available on @{"Aminet" link Aminet}.
@endnode

@node Inventory "Inventory"
    @{fg highlight}Inventory :@{fg text} Modules list.

@{"Modules" link Modules} files are named in the same fashion. The first eight characters of
the file name are the module name displayed by @{"AIBB" link AIBB}.

Modules are sorted according to the kind of central unit.  Several modules
may  correspond  to a same  central unit  and possible  accelerator  board
setup  :  other parameters may change, as Kickstart version, relocation in
Fast RAM, arithmetics coprocessor, etc

        @{"     A500      " link A500 }
        @{"     A600      " link A600 }
        @{"     A1000     " link A1000}  The venerable ancestor...
        @{"     A1200     " link A1200}
        @{"     A2000     " link A2000}  First Zorro II machine
        @{"     A3000     " link A3000}  First Zorro III machine
        @{"     A4000     " link A4000}  First AGA machine
        @{"     CD-32     " link CD-32}  Game console with CD-ROM


Copyright ©1994, 1995 Yann-Erick Proy. All rights reserved.
@endnode

@node AmigaReport "Amiga Report"
    @{fg highlight}Amiga Report :@{fg text} An electronic magazine dedicated to the Amiga.

@{u}Amiga Report@{uu} is  an electronic magazine dedicated to  the Amiga and edited
by @{i}Jason Compton @{ui} (@{fg fill}jcompton@cup.portal.com@{fg text}).

@{u}Amiga Report@{uu}  is available on  @{"Aminet" link Aminet}  (@{b}docs/mags@{ub})  or by suscribing  to a
mailing list (send a short message to Jason). You can also read it without
downloading it with the help of Mosaic :

@{fg fill}http://www.omnipresence.com/Amiga/News/AR/@{fg text}

The module of the  Cyberstorm 40/40  board was found in the  2.31 issue of
@{u}Amiga Report@{uu} and is included here with the permission of Jason Compton.
@endnode

@node Aminet "Aminet"
    @{fg highlight}Aminet :@{fg text} A network of FTP servers for the Amiga.

@{u}Aminet@{uu} designates a federation of FTP sites, lead by @{i}Urban Dominik Mueller @{ui}
(@{fg fill}umueller@wuarchive.wustl.edu@{fg text}). Every "@{u}Aminet@{uu}" site has the same directory
hierarchy inside a  @{b}/pub/aminet@{ub} root and daily exchange 	 the new files up-
loaded to each other.

These are a few addresses of @{u}Aminet@{uu} conformant sites :

    @{fg fill}wuarchive.wustl.edu  @{fg text} (central site)
    @{fg fill}amiga.physik.unizh.ch@{fg text} (origin site)
    @{fg fill}ftp.luth.se          @{fg text}
    @{fg fill}ftp.uni-paderborn.de @{fg text}
    @{fg fill}ftp.src.doc.uk       @{fg text}
    @{fg fill}ftp.cnam.fr          @{fg text} (Finally an @{u}Aminet@{uu} site in France !)

The @{u}Aminet-Weekly@{uu} and @{u}Aminet-Daily@{uu} mailing lists enable you to know perio-
dically which are  the new files.  Send an  "HELP" message to  the address
@{fg fill}listserv@wunet.wustl.edu@{fg text} to know how to suscribe.
@endnode

@node Rights "Rights"
    @{fg highlight}Rights :@{fg text} Restrictions of use

All rights for reproduction of programs and files reserved.
Copyright ©1994 Yann-Erick Proy.

The use and distribution  of the files composing @{u}CompilAIBB@{uu} are subject to
the acceptance  of the following  rules.  If you can't obey them,  destroy
these files and forget them.

These files,  modules and  documentation,  are proposed to you without any
warrenty of any sort, particularly of relevance or fitness to a given pur-
pose.  By no means, the author could be held liable of the consequences of
the use of these files.

@{u}CompilAIBB@{uu} may be freely distributed on condition that :

  1- the original form under which its author has published it is res-
     pected ;

  2- the price asked for its diffusion  is not more than usually asked
     for Fish floppies ($3, 15 FF, etc) or CDs ($30, 200 FF, etc) ;

  3- the diffusion may stop immediately if asked so by the author.
@endnode

